Anonymous Tue 11 Jun 2019 11:55:57 No.23677863 Report
Quoted By:
>>23669318
Your premise doesn't require magic. Just go sci fi & First Contact. The story such as you've hinted will be fine without magic.

As was mentioned by another poster, mixing sci fi & magic is advanced writing trickery. It's rarely ever pulled off well, even by some of the world-class writers. Outline and start structuring your story without any magic. As you progress, see if there are any plot points that require magic, see if you can use sci fi alternates. Only rub magic into it if it is absolutely required and will truly benefit the overall plot.

Alternatively, just go full fantasy and have your humans set in a universe of magic where they are exploring by dimension-hopping rather than interstellar tech travel. If you aren't real strong on advanced planetary, interstellar, and astrophysics science, going full fantasy might be your better option. Harry Potter worked because Rowling didn't explain things, she just made them up and 'magic does All The Things' was good enough for any contradictions. She didn't (and doesn't) have the brains & education to do Asimov or Herbert or Brin or Clarke or Niven or Pournelle, etc. tier world building. But she could come up with clever names and language hacks to invoke imagination, and now she's a multiple billionaire.

Basically, trying to mix them puts you in the position of a sci fi universe where "magic" is a specific field & application of "science." You end up having to come up with a clever way to explain magic as a scientific phenomena. If you really want to go there, try reading Barbara Hambly's The Time of the Dark or The Witches of Wenshar. She's one of the few authors that ever pulled the mix off decently. Some of the old Andre Norton stories from the 1950s & 1960s pulled it off, too. Larry Niven wrote a couple of thought provoking sets of shorts on this theme with The Magic Goes Away and The Magic May Return.
